<font color="#FF0000">ANSWERS FOR LIEN</font><br>
<tt>Fri Apr 25  3:00:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Lien, <br><br>
I have been trying to keep up with this site for a couple of days now, and answer your questions.  But it seems to have taken a different twist.  So before I can begin to answer your questions of veterans, I feel it necessary to enter into the fray with Barry Spatz.  So pardon me for a moment, while I take care of some business.<br><br>
'doc' Spatz, you are a racist!  There is simply no way of denying it, and it is ugly.  The things you have posted here are not what you would have posted had you not known Lien's race/national origin.  Had she been born a year or two later (in the USA), identified herself as &quot;Betty&quot; and asked her questions in the third person instead of in the first person, your answers would have been much different.  What really surprises me is that with your knowledge-base that you do not realize the inherent racism in which we are daily immersed, and the propensity for all of us to react in a racist manner because this is how our society has conditioned us (meaning &quot;whites&quot;) since birth. I know this to be true because I have brought up these same issues on other threads at this site, and you have not responded in this manner to me. <br><br>
People who deny this inherent racism are much like fish in the sea denying that they breath salt water. The fish are so immersed in it, and only know that one medium, that they cannot recognize it.  So to are you so immersed in a racist society that you cannot recognize your own racist writings. Perhaps by being called on it here, you will recognize this abhorrent behavior when you next engage in it.<br><br>
Concerning your practice, and the number of Vietnamese leeching off the system, I have worked for many years in Oregon's workers' compensation system and I'm here to tell you that there are many, many people whom you would describe as &quot;white&quot; who are doing the same thing.  Yes, many people do it and any population will have its share; I don't judge any population by an unrepresentative sample of individuals, especially when the information is &quot;hearsay.&quot;<br><br>
Doc Del, please let me know about those other sites; you don't have to tackle them by yourself.  But, thank you for doing it.  One of the biggest obsticles to peace and hormonious living is racist attitudes, and those individuals who harbor these kinds of attitudes need to be confronted concerning them.<br><br>
Lien, you did ask some pertainent questions.  I can only speak for myself, but I welcome you to our country (its yours as well as mine).  I deeply feel that we need all the diverse cultures so that we can see what this world is all about.  We do need some commonality, consisting of respect for each other and the constitution upon which this nation is built.  But we also need to change things which need changing (for instance, my marriage to a Chinese woman would have been &quot;illegal&quot; as late as the 1950s in some places).  <br><br>
You asked about the then little girl, Kim Phue, and our reactions to her photograph after being burned by napalm.  It is one of many images which seared me, as a medic (USAF pararescueman), and the nation's conscience.  There are a couple of things which need to be said though.  First, I believe that the pilot was Vietnamese, not American.  The second is that she is extremely lucky to be alive, and were it not for the efforts of many personnel, both Vietnamese and American, she would surely have died of her burns.<br><br>
An even greater point is this, that image did not compare to the impact of trying to aid people hit by a North Vietnamese rocket when it dead-centered a Vietnamese home at DaNang Air Field where a family was sleeping.  We had to run a few hundred yards to the remains of the home, and were too late to help with the wounded (a little boy with an amputated leg).  I went into the hulk, and remember thinking, &quot;Where are those people?&quot;  Then I started looking, and smelling, that they were all around me, splattered against the walls and ceiling.  Where there were three other people just minutes before, a family sleeping in a supposedly &quot;safe&quot; place, now there were just pieces of flesh no larger than my fist, and the distinct odor of aerosolized human beings. We stayed for awhile and helped the Vietnamese officials gather the remains, as much as possible under the circumstances.<br><br>
Now, let me address some of the reactions you have received as a Vietnamese person from others that has been negative.  I will not address some of the stories I have placed at other posts on this site about the prejudice experienced by Vietnamese in the USA.  <br><br>
It is my belief that your (Vietnamese peoples) presence in the USA does bring back bad memories, and not only to Vietnam Veterans.  Your presence, and the &quot;Little Saigon&quot; sign, is tangible evidence that the ideals that the protestors espoused were hollow.  I did not see 'doc' Spatz mention anything about the same feelings for Koreatown or Chinatown, so I assume it is only the Vietnamese for whom he feels resentment.<br><br>
The protestors claim &quot;victory&quot; where there could be none.  Their support of the Viet Cong and North Vietnamese during the war registers today as their support for displacing a whole population of people.  The &quot;Little Saigon&quot; sign on the LA freeway even today sears 'doc' Spatz conscience because it shows the betrayal of his ideals by those he supported during the war.  I may be wrong (tell me, 'doc' if I am), but it seems to me that this is the underlying reason that some former protesters resent the Vietnamese people who have settled here.  It could also explain the bitterness evidenced by 'doc' Spatz's recent posts here.<br><br>
Well, it's late, and while I do have more thoughts on this subject, they will have to wait.<br>

<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


